{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01DEi5XduuoujPcBmG1kKudL","type":"tool_result","content":"# Askewly Design Principles: Core Summary\n\n## Task-First Hierarchy\n\nThe system prioritizes user work over decoration. As stated: \"Choose the product surface and the user's job before choosing components.\" This means establishing semantic structure and content hierarchy before visual treatment. Each viewport needs one dominant action, with supporting elements demoted through spacing, type, and borders rather than competing fills.\n\n## Meaningful Motion\n\nMotion must clarify change, not ornament. The design remains coherent when animation pauses, with \"short transitions to reveal causality or state change.\" Every animation needs a valid resting state—perpetual activity without purpose reads as distraction rather than product behavior.\n\n## Additional Core Principles\n\n**Token Discipline:** Semantic and component tokens describe intent; primitive values and ad hoc dimensions leak into code only when system tokens don't exist.\n\n**Specific Evidence:** Examples prove reusable capability in real context. Fake metrics and decorative elements replace authentic content and interaction only when they serve no purpose.\n\n**Complete Interactions:** Components include keyboard navigation, focus behavior, empty states, errors, and responsive fallback—not just the happy path.\n\n**Earned Trust:** Public surfaces expose only finished work. Unfinished definitions stay behind development gates until content, readability, and interaction pass their criteria.\n\n**System Integrity:** External references inform Askewly's identity; they don't replace it. Learned patterns adapt through Askewly tokens and contracts, not reproduction of another product's signature."}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"05f608d7-b1fc-4ad3-a101-9110f925f986","uuid":"520068e8-c061-4731-beec-1172b11e18ef","timestamp":"2026-07-18T12:31:58.640Z","tool_use_result":{"bytes":7821,"code":200,"codeText":"OK","result":"# Askewly Design Principles: Core Summary\n\n## Task-First Hierarchy\n\nThe system prioritizes user work over decoration. As stated: \"Choose the product surface and the user's job before choosing components.\" This means establishing semantic structure and content hierarchy before visual treatment. Each viewport needs one dominant action, with supporting elements demoted through spacing, type, and borders rather than competing fills.\n\n## Meaningful Motion\n\nMotion must clarify change, not ornament. The design remains coherent when animation pauses, with \"short transitions to reveal causality or state change.\" Every animation needs a valid resting state—perpetual activity without purpose reads as distraction rather than product behavior.\n\n## Additional Core Principles\n\n**Token Discipline:** Semantic and component tokens describe intent; primitive values and ad hoc dimensions leak into code only when system tokens don't exist.\n\n**Specific Evidence:** Examples prove reusable capability in real context. Fake metrics and decorative elements replace authentic content and interaction only when they serve no purpose.\n\n**Complete Interactions:** Components include keyboard navigation, focus behavior, empty states, errors, and responsive fallback—not just the happy path.\n\n**Earned Trust:** Public surfaces expose only finished work. Unfinished definitions stay behind development gates until content, readability, and interaction pass their criteria.\n\n**System Integrity:** External references inform Askewly's identity; they don't replace it. Learned patterns adapt through Askewly tokens and contracts, not reproduction of another product's signature.","durationMs":5649,"url":"https://ui.askewly.com/llms/docs/design-system/principles.md"}}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01L5mgzzmxzJzJ116GyBjPmq","type":"tool_result","content":"# Askewly Style: 5 Operating Principles\n\nBased on the document, these are the five principles for judging design output quality:\n\n1. **Token Derivation** — \"모든 색·치수는 프로젝트 토큰에서 파생한다\" (all colors and dimensions derive from project tokens; no invented literals).\n\n2. **Accent as Signal** — \"강조색은 primary action·선택 상태·상태 표시 같은 신호로 소면적만 쓴다\" (emphasis colors function as indicators, applied sparingly to small surfaces only).\n\n3. **Restrained Hierarchy** — One focal point per viewport; establish layering through spacing, typography, borders, and surface changes before applying competing emphasis.\n\n4. **Complete States** — All relevant interaction states (hover, focus, active, disabled, empty, error) must be present and functional in both light and dark modes.\n\n5. **Experimental Touch is Manual** — Intentional asymmetries, overlaps, and decorative experiments should not be agent-initiated; they require explicit human approval or instruction.\n\nThese principles prioritize systematic thinking over fixed aesthetics, ensuring consistency through *process* rather than prescriptive rules."}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"05f608d7-b1fc-4ad3-a101-9110f925f986","uuid":"f6e79197-94df-45a3-98c7-84715f97ed44","timestamp":"2026-07-18T12:31:58.766Z","tool_use_result":{"bytes":4325,"code":200,"codeText":"OK","result":"# Askewly Style: 5 Operating Principles\n\nBased on the document, these are the five principles for judging design output quality:\n\n1. **Token Derivation** — \"모든 색·치수는 프로젝트 토큰에서 파생한다\" (all colors and dimensions derive from project tokens; no invented literals).\n\n2. **Accent as Signal** — \"강조색은 primary action·선택 상태·상태 표시 같은 신호로 소면적만 쓴다\" (emphasis colors function as indicators, applied sparingly to small surfaces only).\n\n3. **Restrained Hierarchy** — One focal point per viewport; establish layering through spacing, typography, borders, and surface changes before applying competing emphasis.\n\n4. **Complete States** — All relevant interaction states (hover, focus, active, disabled, empty, error) must be present and functional in both light and dark modes.\n\n5. **Experimental Touch is Manual** — Intentional asymmetries, overlaps, and decorative experiments should not be agent-initiated; they require explicit human approval or instruction.\n\nThese principles prioritize systematic thinking over fixed aesthetics, ensuring consistency through *process* rather than prescriptive rules.","durationMs":4862,"url":"https://ui.askewly.com/llms/docs/design-system/style-signature.md"}}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01RVoWjvc8Mzd4NWTzwuqgxo","type":"tool_result","content":"# Anti-Patterns for Forms & Marketing Banners with Email Input\n\nBased on the guide, here are critical patterns to avoid:\n\n## 1. **Destructive Action Protection** (#2)\nDon't style submit buttons identically to regular actions. \"Deletive or broad-impact operations should be visually distinguished and allow review before immediate reflection.\" For email signup, clarify what submitting actually does (e.g., \"Subscribe\" vs. \"Join\").\n\n## 2. **Keyboard & Accessibility Paths** (#3)\nEnsure email fields and buttons work via keyboard (Tab, Enter). Never rely on hover or swipe alone. Focus must return properly after modal close.\n\n## 3. **State Signals Beyond Color** (#4)\nDon't signal validation errors, success, or urgency with color only. Pair visual feedback with text labels or `aria-label` attributes.\n\n## 4. **Empty States by Cause** (#5)\nIf signup fails, distinguish the reason: \"Invalid email format\" vs. \"Server unavailable\" vs. \"Already subscribed.\" Offer recovery actions (retry, format hint, contact support).\n\n## 5. **No Surprise Costs** (#1)\nFor banner CTAs with commerce intent, display all fees upfront. Hide nothing until confirmation.\n\n## 6. **Single-Source State** (#6)\nIf showing a character counter or validation message alongside the input, derive both from one state source to prevent drift.\n\n## 7. **Typography & CJK Wrapping** (#13)\nApply `break-keep` CSS to email field labels and button text in Korean contexts. Test with real Korean copy—don't rely on English mockups.\n\n---\n\n**Key takeaway:** Forms should prioritize accessibility (keyboard + screen reader), clear error causes, and consistent state, while avoiding visual-only feedback and surprise friction."}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"05f608d7-b1fc-4ad3-a101-9110f925f986","uuid":"fbd1e238-9e9a-4d9a-8b97-8df74fbbbf8d","timestamp":"2026-07-18T12:31:59.044Z","tool_use_result":{"bytes":21544,"code":200,"codeText":"OK","result":"# Anti-Patterns for Forms & Marketing Banners with Email Input\n\nBased on the guide, here are critical patterns to avoid:\n\n## 1. **Destructive Action Protection** (#2)\nDon't style submit buttons identically to regular actions. \"Deletive or broad-impact operations should be visually distinguished and allow review before immediate reflection.\" For email signup, clarify what submitting actually does (e.g., \"Subscribe\" vs. \"Join\").\n\n## 2. **Keyboard & Accessibility Paths** (#3)\nEnsure email fields and buttons work via keyboard (Tab, Enter). Never rely on hover or swipe alone. Focus must return properly after modal close.\n\n## 3. **State Signals Beyond Color** (#4)\nDon't signal validation errors, success, or urgency with color only. Pair visual feedback with text labels or `aria-label` attributes.\n\n## 4. **Empty States by Cause** (#5)\nIf signup fails, distinguish the reason: \"Invalid email format\" vs. \"Server unavailable\" vs. \"Already subscribed.\" Offer recovery actions (retry, format hint, contact support).\n\n## 5. **No Surprise Costs** (#1)\nFor banner CTAs with commerce intent, display all fees upfront. Hide nothing until confirmation.\n\n## 6. **Single-Source State** (#6)\nIf showing a character counter or validation message alongside the input, derive both from one state source to prevent drift.\n\n## 7. **Typography & CJK Wrapping** (#13)\nApply `break-keep` CSS to email field labels and button text in Korean contexts. Test with real Korean copy—don't rely on English mockups.\n\n---\n\n**Key takeaway:** Forms should prioritize accessibility (keyboard + screen reader), clear error causes, and consistent state, while avoiding visual-only feedback and surprise friction.","durationMs":6758,"url":"https://ui.askewly.com/llms/docs/design-system/anti-patterns.md"}}
